<div class="post"><div class="posttop"><div class="username">Eniarch</div><div class="date">February 9th, 2012, 06:49 AM</div></div><div class="posttext">I never did any smithing besides the first couple of newbie tasks. As a mage, I never saw the point. Especially since I accidentally became Arch Mage early on and pretty much kept that robe until the end of the game (switched occasionally for the thieves guild armor for carrying capacity).Well, the most obvious case is for companion gear. Most mages are taking a heavier combat companion along, and being able to hand them a set of highly honed and improved gear does make a pronounced difference, IMO. Better bows give them better standoff capability, better armor means fewer reloads and less healing drains, better melee weapons give them the means to help out with overrunning hordes. Since the companions have adopted the FO3/NV equipment selection system, they'll equip and benefit from your output. (This also applies to enchanting, obviously.)<br />
<br />
Improved backup weapons (if you're not using daedric spells) and using improved armor (often boots/gauntlets/helm) to fill out an outfit of mage clothing can provide some benefits. (Less so, if you're taking Alteration perks that work only when not wearing armor items.) Often early on, I'm carrying a sharpened dagger or one-hand sword, and an improved bow, even though I'm a mage. (Mana's not infinite, and bows can sneak attack at range!) Later, the ability to improve enchanted weapons and armor can give you the ability to improve even fairly powerful items you want to use. (I spent time improving the bow I got during the DB assassination missions, frex.)<br />
<br />
Improved items sell for a little more money, and it's not hard to have large quantities of ore saved up if you stop into every mine you find and mine every ore vein you find (even if you won't use it). What's a companion for, if not to carry my pickaxe, woodcutter's axe, shovel, crowbar, and kitchen sink like a good little pack mule?<br />
<br />
Finally, there's the &quot;I'm going to take that dragon, drag it out of the sky, eat its soul and forge arms and armor from its body&quot; factor, which may or may not matter to you.</div></div><hr />


